1. Preparation¶

Nowadays,estimated by the SIPP(The Survey of Income and Program Participation),1 in 20 Americans are currently deaf or hard of hearing.As the hearing problems are more popular in our life,the communication between deaf sign language users and spoken language users is becoming harder.The sign language translater will be in high demand in the future. We choose the dataset for alphabets in American Sign Language, so that we could use CNN to better recognize and classify each one to provide better analysis.

The training dataset contains 87000 training images of English alphabets,which belongs to 29 categories.There are 3000 images of each category.The testing dataset has one image from each of the characters listed above.The size of each image is about 200x200 pixels.

Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/grassknoted/asl-alphabet

1.1 Choose metric¶

There are four common evaluation metrics: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score. In order to choose the appropriate metric, we need to compare these different metrics based on our data. Use letter A as example, we want to get the letter A after recognizing the gesture image which actually represents letter A, it is the best result we want, we can use True Positive to describe this condition. If we use gesture image which actually represents letter B, but the prediction result is letter A, this condition is False Positive. If we use gesture image which actually represents letter A, but the prediction result is letter B, this condition is False Negative. And the last condition is True negative which means we use gesture image which actually represents letter B and we get the result the letter is not A. The reason why we mention these four conditions is they are related to four common evaluation metrics. Accuracy indicates how many proportions of our sample are correct, this includes both TP and TN, however we want to focus on TP because it is what we would like to use in practical application. We hope people can recognize letter A from gesture image A instead of knowing the gesture image is not A and the letter is also not A. Next, considering Precision, Recall and F1-score together. Precision reflects the ability to identify negative sample, Recall reflects the ability to identify positive sample, they are both focus on TP, F1-score is the combination of these two metrics and it find a balance between Precision and Recall, so F1-score is better for our data. And for our business circumstances, most people can't recognize the sign language which corresponding to our data is that we need to improve actual large negatives to become positives, F1-score is also good for this uneven condition. Therefore, we decide to select F1-score as our metric.

There are two ways to calculate the average in F1-score: macro and micro. Macro is to calculate the TP in each category, based on our data, we can get total 2*29 values of both percision and recall, we calculate the average of each 29 values for precision and recall, then apply them to f1 formula. Micro is to combine TP for 29 categories together, get one value for precision and recall, then apply them to f1 formula. If data of each category is unbalanced, micro is preferred. However, in our data, each category has 3000 images which means distribution is balanced, so we can use macro method.

Reference:
1.https://towardsdatascience.com/accuracy-precision-recall-or-f1-331fb37c5cb9
2.http://sofasofa.io/forum_main_post.php?postid=1001112

1.2 Choose cross validation method¶

We are considering Stratified K-fold and stratified Shuffle splits as cross validation methods for our model. They are both shuffle the data and split the data into n_splits parts. However, there are some differences between them. For Stratified K-fold, every sample is in one fold and it only shuffles data one time before splitting. And training proportion in each iteration is k-1/k. For stratified Shuffle splits, it randomly shuffles each time before splitting and splits n_splits time, so test sets can overlap, but it is also possible that some samples are neither in the training set nor the testing set. The training proportion in each iteration is based on train_size. In our data, we want to test the accuracy of identify gesture image as right letter. Since in stratified Shuffle splits, data can be shuffled each time before splitting, it will increase the diversity and complexity of data which meets our requirements in actual life because when gesture images translater can be implemented in the future, the data collected should be diverse so that the accuracy of identify correctly is high, even though gesture images are complex, and it will increase the business application value. So we would like to use stratified Shuffle splits as our cross validation method.

Reference:
1.https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/270620/what-is-the-benefit-of-only-performing-a-random-split-once-at-the-beginning-duri 2.https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45969390/difference-between-stratifiedkfold-and-stratifiedshufflesplit-in-sklearn

2.1.1 Data Expansion¶

Since we have a large dataset, so we decide to randomly select samples as our dataset for this lab. After selection, the data set has 17400 samples.

In order to creat CNN model, we need to use data expansion in Keras. We get the idea for data expansion from 11. Convolutional Neural Networks.ipynb and 12. More Advanced CNN Techniques.ipynb which provided in class. First, We decide to convert the data to the appropriate type and np.array format, then we need to reshape the data to the dimension which we need to use in CNN. And for y which represents label, we use keras.utils.to_categorical to do one more expansion. After getting y, we first use stratified Shuffle splits to get y_train and y_test, then do keras.utils.to_categorical to get y_train_ohe,y_test_ohe so that we can implement them in cnn models.

The data expansion process is appropriate for our data because the accuracy we get is good whcih can reach 0.99 in final CNNs, we have tried other data expansion techniques, however, the accuracy is around 0.4, even only 0.06 in first simple CNN, so we think the data expansion technique we use is appropriate.

The code we used in the following cell are all from reference https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43547402/how-to-calculate-f1-macro-in-keras¶

# The code we used in the following cell are all from reference https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43547402/how-to-calculate-f1-macro-in-keras
from keras import backend as K

def f1score(y_true, y_pred):
    def recall(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        possible_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1)))
        recall = true_positives / (possible_positives + K.epsilon())
        return recall

    def precision(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        predicted_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_pred, 0, 1)))
        precision = true_positives / (predicted_positives + K.epsilon())
        return precision
    precision = precision(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = recall(y_true, y_pred)
    return 2*((precision*recall)/(precision+recall+K.epsilon()))

%%time 


cnn = Sequential()

# let's start with an AlexNet style convolutional phase
cnn.add(Conv2D(filters=32,
                input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,3),
                kernel_size=(3,3), 
                padding='same', 
                activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")) # more compact syntax

# no max pool before next conv layer!!
cnn.add(Conv2D(filters=64,
                kernel_size=(3,3), 
                padding='same', 
                activation='relu')) # more compact syntax
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last"))


# add one layer on flattened output
cnn.add(Dropout(0.25)) # add some dropout for regularization after conv layers
cnn.add(Flatten())
cnn.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
cnn.add(Dropout(0.5)) # add some dropout for regularization, again!
cnn.add(Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='softmax'))

cnn.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=[f1score])
print(cnn.summary())
cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=2)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, NUM_CLASSES)
    y_test_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, NUM_CLASSES)
    
    history = cnn.fit_generator(datagen.flow(X_train, y_train_ohe, batch_size=32), 
                       steps_per_epoch=int(len(X_train)/32), # how many generators to go through per epoch
                       epochs=10, verbose=1,
                       validation_data=(X_test,y_test_ohe))
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1score'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1score'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('categorical_crossentropy Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

def summarize_net(net, X_test, y_test, title_text=''):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    yhat = np.argmax(net.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    acc = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat,average='macro')
    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat)
    cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
    plt.title(title_text+'{:.4f}'.format(acc))

# now lets use the LeNet architecture with batch norm
# We will also use ReLU where approriate and drop out 
from keras.layers.normalization import BatchNormalization
from keras.layers import Add
from keras.layers import average, concatenate
from keras.models import Input, Model

input_holder = Input(shape=(img_wh, img_wh, 3))
l2_lambda = 0.0001

# start with a conv layer
x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,3),
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(input_holder)

x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

x_split = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=64,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x_split)

x = Conv2D(filters=64,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(1,1),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

# now add back in the split layer, x_split (residual added in)
x = Add()([x, x_split])
x = Activation("relu")(x)

x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dropout(0.25)(x)
x = Dense(256)(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES)(x)
x = Activation('softmax')(x)

resnet = Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)

resnet.summary()

resnet.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', # 'categorical_crossentropy' 'mean_squared_error'
                optimizer='rmsprop', # 'adadelta' 'rmsprop'
                metrics=[f1score])

# the flow method yields batches of images indefinitely, with the given transofmrations
# resnet.fit_generator(datagen.flow(X_train, y_train_ohe, batch_size=128), 
#                       steps_per_epoch=int(len(X_train)/128), # how many generators to go through per epoch
#                       epochs=50, verbose=1,
#                       validation_data=(X_test,y_test_ohe),
#                       callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=4)]
#                      )
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, NUM_CLASSES)
    y_test_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, NUM_CLASSES)
    
    history = resnet.fit(X_train, y_train_ohe, batch_size=32, 
                      epochs=10, verbose=1,
                      validation_data=(X_test,y_test_ohe),
                      callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=4)]
                     )
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1score'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')

    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)

2.2.3 Ensemble Nets¶

In [28]:
%%time

from keras.layers import average, concatenate
from keras.models import Input, Model


num_ensembles = 3
l2_lambda = 0.000001

input_holder = Input(shape=(img_wh, img_wh, 3))

# start with a conv layer
x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")(input_holder)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu')(x)
input_conv = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

branches = []
for _ in range(num_ensembles):
    
    # start using NiN (MLPConv)
    x = Conv2D(filters=32,
                   input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
                   kernel_size=(3,3),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(input_conv)

    x = Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=(1,1),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters=64,
                   input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
                   kernel_size=(3,3),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(x)

    x = Conv2D(filters=64,
                   kernel_size=(1,1),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

    # add one layer on flattened output
    x = Flatten()(x)
    x = Dropout(0.50)(x) # add some dropout for regularization after conv layers
    x = Dense(64, 
              activation='relu',
              kernel_initializer='he_uniform',
              kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
            )(x)
    
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='relu',
              kernel_initializer='he_uniform',
              kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
             )(x)
    
    # now add this branch onto the master list
    branches.append(x)

# that's it, we just need to average the results
x = concatenate(branches)

x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, 
          activation='softmax', 
          kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform',
          kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
         )(x)

# here is the secret sauce for setting the network using the 
#   Functional API:
cnn_ens = Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)

cnn_ens.summary()

cnn_ens.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', # 'categorical_crossentropy' 'mean_squared_error'
                optimizer='rmsprop', # 'adadelta' 'rmsprop'
                metrics=[f1score])

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, NUM_CLASSES)
    y_test_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, NUM_CLASSES)
    
    history = cnn_ens.fit(X_train, y_train_ohe, batch_size=32, 
                      epochs=10, verbose=1,
                      validation_data=(X_test,y_test_ohe),
                      callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=4)]
                     )
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1score'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1score'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('categorical_crossentropy Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

Change l2_lambda¶

%%time

from keras.layers import average, concatenate
from keras.models import Input, Model


num_ensembles = 3
l2_lambda = 0.0001

input_holder = Input(shape=(img_wh, img_wh, 3))

# start with a conv layer
x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")(input_holder)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu')(x)
input_conv = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

branches = []
for _ in range(num_ensembles):
    
    # start using NiN (MLPConv)
    x = Conv2D(filters=32,
                   input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
                   kernel_size=(3,3),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(input_conv)

    x = Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=(1,1),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters=64,
                   input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
                   kernel_size=(3,3),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(x)

    x = Conv2D(filters=64,
                   kernel_size=(1,1),
                   kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
                   kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='linear', data_format="channels_last")(x)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

    # add one layer on flattened output
    x = Flatten()(x)
    x = Dropout(0.50)(x) # add some dropout for regularization after conv layers
    x = Dense(64, 
              activation='relu',
              kernel_initializer='he_uniform',
              kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
            )(x)
    
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='relu',
              kernel_initializer='he_uniform',
              kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
             )(x)
    
    # now add this branch onto the master list
    branches.append(x)

# that's it, we just need to average the results
x = concatenate(branches)

x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, 
          activation='softmax', 
          kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform',
          kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)
         )(x)

# here is the secret sauce for setting the network using the 
#   Functional API:
cnn_ens2 = Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)

cnn_ens2.summary()

cnn_ens2.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', # 'categorical_crossentropy' 'mean_squared_error'
                optimizer='rmsprop', # 'adadelta' 'rmsprop'
                metrics=[f1score])

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, NUM_CLASSES)
    y_test_ohe =  keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, NUM_CLASSES)
    
    history = cnn_ens2.fit(X_train, y_train_ohe, batch_size=32, 
                      epochs=10, verbose=1,
                      validation_data=(X_test,y_test_ohe),
                      callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=4)]
                     )
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1score'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1score'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('categorical_crossentropy Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

from sklearn import metrics as mt
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

def compare_cnn(cnn, cnn2, cnn3, resnet,resnet2,cnn_ens,cnn_ens1,cnn_ens2, X_test, y_test):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=1.5,wspace = 0.2,hspace = 0.5)
    if cnn is not None:
        yhat_cnn = np.argmax(cnn.predict(X_test), axis=1)
        acc_cnn = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat_cnn,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(4,2,1)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
        plt.title('CNN: '+str(acc_cnn))
        
    if cnn2 is not None:
        yhat_cnn2 = np.argmax(cnn2.predict(X_test), axis=1)
        acc_cnn2 = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat_cnn2,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(4,2,2)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn2)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
        plt.title('CNN2: '+str(acc_cnn2))
        
    if cnn3 is not None:
        yhat_cnn3 = np.argmax(cnn3.predict(X_test), axis=1)
        acc_cnn3 = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat_cnn3,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(4,2,3)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn3)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]

        plt.title('CNN3: '+str(acc_cnn3))

        yhat_resnet = np.argmax(resnet.predict(X_test), axis=1)

        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_resnet2)

        yhat_cnn_ens = np.argmax(cnn_ens.predict(X_test), axis=1)
        acc_cnn_ens = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat_cnn_ens,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(4,2,6)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn_ens)

The ROC of MLP¶

In [72]:
from scipy import interp

def plot_roc(probas, y_true):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    mean_tpr = 0.0
    mean_fpr = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
    all_tpr = []

    classes = np.unique(y_true)
    perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
    roc_auc = 0
    for j in classes:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = mt.roc_curve(y_true, probas[:, j], pos_label=j)
        perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
        perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
        roc_auc += mt.auc(fpr, tpr)
        plt.plot(fpr,tpr,'--',lw=.5,label='Class ROC Fold, AUC=%0.2f'
                     %(mt.auc(fpr, tpr)) )

    perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
    roc_auc /= len(classes)
    mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr

    plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'-',lw=2,label='Mean Class ROC Fold, AUC=%0.2f'
                     %(roc_auc))
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.xlabel('false positive rate')
    plt.ylabel('true positive rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')

In [55]:
from sklearn import metrics as mt
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

def compare_mlp_ens1(cnn_ens1, mlp, X_test, y_test, X_test_vector_mlp,y_test_mlp):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    if cnn_ens1 is not None:
        yhat_cnn_ens1 = np.argmax(cnn_ens1.predict(X_test), axis=1)
        acc_cnn_ens1 = mt.f1_score(y_test,yhat_cnn_ens1,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(1,2,1)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn_ens1)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
        plt.title('Ensemble: '+str(acc_cnn_ens1))
    
    if mlp is not None:
        yhat_mlp = np.argmax(mlp.predict(X_test_vector_mlp), axis=1)
        acc_mlp = mt.f1_score(y_test_mlp,yhat_mlp,average='macro')
        plt.subplot(1,2,2)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test_mlp,yhat_mlp)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True, fmt='.2f')
        plt.title('MLP: '+str(acc_mlp))
